div.head: Zach Bryan - God Speed from the album DeAnn The song “God Speed” by Zach Bryan is a song that focuses on the theme of perseverance. Zach discusses the hardships that he faces in life, yet he finds ways to to continue driving with his work and will eventually be able to reach the happiness that he desires. He discusses in the song the courage it takes to move forward and let your past mistakes go, all while being open to risks that you may have to take in the future. He really encourages you to not worry about the outcome of the future and to enjoy where you are in life.

lg.l: I like the way your face looks
When you're smiling like a vandal To smile like a vandal is to smile a mischievous smile.
Waking up warm with you in a room
That's too cold for us to handle
And in this shack I'm living in
You don't mind sleeping in
Eating food leftover from last night
There's plenty of boys that want you, babe
But for me you will crawl and scratch, and fight
So we'll go out on Saturday
And ride the bronco through the bay
Sit and drink cerveza by the shore
You'll tell me you love me, girl
Even if I'm wrecked, lonely, and poor
So don't give up on me These last few lines show the theme of perseverance by asking the girl to persevere through his worst times
You don't care where I'm buying
You're in
Girls today will drink all day
To fall in love with any boy they see
You're a sight of utmost beauty
Utmost strength and utmost loyalty
So I'll sit here and drink all night
And talk about the Lord's delight in you
If my mama could just see you laugh
I know that she could see the shine in you
She'd say thanks for taking care
Of her baby boy 'cause she can't be here
And hug you 'til your little lungs turn blue To hug someone till their lungs turn blue means to hug someone tightly and to not let them go
No, I won't give up on you
No, I won't give up on you These last two line are showing the theme of perseverance through Zach saying no matter what he will not give up on this person he loves

div.head: Zach Bryan - Come as You Are from the album Elisabeth The song “Come as You Are” by Zach Bryan has a theme of comradery. Zach talks about the challenges that he and his friends have faced in their lifetime, from issues such as substance abuse to depression. He talks about how his friends have been accepting of each other’s flaws, and that they help each other become “whole” again. These friendships that are making him whole are important because this is what allows him to feel like he is not alone. There are also references to a nostalgic theme reflecting on the good times that have been had in the past.

lg.l: I've got some good friends with some loose ends
That remind me of myself
They can drink as much as me
And they can smoke me half to hell
And by the end of these songs
When we bring our asses home
They'll all be thankin' God
That they're not in this pain alone These first couple lines show that he feels that he is not alone in his struggles
And this world has been so cruel to me
And it's been the same to them
But I don't mind sharin' my sweet depression
With some boys that act just like me
And a girl who does the same
I don't know how I got here
But I'm glad as hell I came
Come as you are, however broken He does not mean literally broken, rather whatever problems you have whether they be mental or physical.
And we will see if we can make you whole again

Come as you are with your heart wide open These last couple lines showcase the meaning of the song, he is saying that he wants people that have similar problems to come together and console each other.
They are still there just floatin'
Remember us in our bright eyed days
Too young to go inside
Sittin' drunk on curbs tryin' to get us ourselves a ride
Of the pretty girls who walk down there on Elgin Avenue
Oklahoma sure is quiet, but it has itself a view
And how am I supposed to know the good times that I'm in
If the good is only seen when I'm lookin' back at them
The boys are gettin' off work
And they're haulin' on back home
If I am meant for anything, it's to show you you're not alone
Come as you are, however broken This is the same meaning as the broken described earlier.
And we will see if we can make you whole again

Come as you are with your heart wide open These last couple lines showcase the meaning of the song, he is saying that he wants people that have similar problems to come together and console each other.
Bridges that you've burned
They are still there just floatin'
I've got some good friends with some loose ends
That remind me of myself
They can drink as much as me
And they can smoke me half to hell
And by the end of these songs
When we bring our asses home
They'll all be thankin' God
We're not in this pain alone
Come as you are, however broken
And we will see if we can make you whole again
Come as you are with your heart wide open
Bridges that you've burned
They are still there just floatin' The end of the song talks about the theme of camaraderie and how they will try to help each other.

div.head: Zach Bryan - Tishomingo from the album American Heartbreak The song “Tishomingo” by Zach Bryan shows the theme of longing. In this song specifically, Zach is talking about longing for a place he can call home. The chorus talks about how he is going down a dark path, and is dreaming about finding a place where he can have “a porch swing with some lights” that he would be able to call his home. He reflects on whether love will really be his guide home, or if it is not true and following love has been leading him astray. He ends the song asking for prayers for guidance to get home in any way possible.

lg.l: Well, I don't think that the city moves slow enough for me
So I'm gonna leave now and I ain't showing no warnings
And I know that mama said that love'll always lead you home
But I've been following this lonely road for way too long
So won't you pray for me tonight?
I've been heading down a dark cold road
I've been dreaming of a porch swing with some lights I tagged this as "home" because this is the feeling of home that Zach wants.
Hoping I can find myself back home
Now, I'm breaking horses out in Tishomingo
And every night I lie there and wonder where good men's dreams go
And most nights I wonder how far train cars can travel
Or how far a man can go before one's truly unraveled This means that he wonders how much a person is able to endure before they give up.
So won't you pray for me tonight?
I've been heading down a dark cold road
And I've been dreaming of a porch swing with some lights
Hoping I can find myself back home
Don't jump in so quick kid, you're gonna wind up hurt
She's with a new man in New York, the last time I heard
And I know that mama said that love'll always lead me home
But I been following a lonely road for way too long
So won't you pray for me tonight?
I've been heading down a dark cold road
I've been dreaming of a you by my side
Praying I can get myself back home The end of this song you come to the realization that the longing for "home" is really just longing for someone to love.

div.head: Zach Bryan - El Dorado from the album Zach Bryan The song “El Dorado” by Zach Bryan is a song that addresses the loss of someone that Zach knew. He talks about the hardships of losing his friend who is now on his way to “El Dorado” the mythical city. He talks about the pain that he has when thinking about his friend that he lost. He talks about the happy memories he has and then reflects on the pain of that friend no longer being around.

lg.l: Did you ever make it back to El Dorado?
I'd call and ask, but hell if I know
If I still got your number or if you care
You moved away when you was younger
Was it escape or was it hunger?
Kansas ain't no place to be a man
You used to say you'd settle down
But that kind girl from school in town
She was gone before you got back home Zach is talking about how his friend used to tell him future plans, but now the situation is different from what they planned.
To El Dorado, hell if I know if you're still alive
There's a note in the glovebox in your drive
El Dorado, hell if they know the difference in a hero
And a man I wish was still by my side These previous two lines you are able to realize that this is about a friend who has died and not just moved away.
Seventeen years old
How our grins look scary brave
My mama always said we look so handsome when we shave
You used to say, "If not you, then who?"
And you'd go a thousand times or two
Now your name's up on a sign in El Dorado driving through These previous three lines talk about how the friend used to be very brave and uplifting, but he is unfortunately no longer around.
In El Dorado, hell if I know if you're still alive
There's a note in the glovebox in your drive
El Dorado, hell if they know the difference in a heroThis was tagged as soldier because the friend who had passed was a soldier.
And a man I wish was still by my side
You're in every last memory alive
And I called last week to talk to my favorite old devil dog
They told me he had finally headed homeThis last line talks about how the person is officially dead and moving on from life on Earth.

div.head: Zach Bryan featuring Noah Kahan- Sarah’s Place from the EP Boys of Faith The song “Sarah’s Place” by Zach Bryan featuring Noah Kahan is a song that focuses on nostalgia. The lyrics bring about a feeling of homesickness, especially due to the fact that someone Zach had cared about is no longer around changing the dynamic of his home town. The song talks about what almost seems like simpler times where they would just sit in the back yard and drink with all his friends. He talks about the change of how things are now and reminiscing about the joyful days he used to have with all of his friends while at “Sarah’s place”.

lg.l: Road dogs are built for sleepin' in
I've been up since 4 AM
At your worst, you're better than my better days He is saying her worst days are better than his best days
There ain't been no sun in LA
Since you moved out of Sarah's place
I love your mother's stories 'bout you as a kid
I heard you scored a job in the east village
While working for some folks who don't know your name
Well, ain't you gonna miss all of them wasted days?
We'd sit around, drinkin' out at Sarah's place The past couple lines are talking about reminiscing on the past good times that were had among a friend group.
Don't come back lover, I'm proud you're under the skyline
We always knew you were the better half of our good times
Those backyard lights don't shine as bright without your face He is saying that now that you are gone nothing is the same
Out at Sarah's Place
And you called to talk just last week
I'm still fallin' apart like I'll always be
And your picnic chair is still sittin' there in the yard He talks about how he sees the chair and is reminded of the past.
And I had to sell my old guitar
But don't come back lover, I'm proud you're under the skyline
We always knew you were the better half of our good times
Those backyard lights don't shine as bright without your face
Out at Sarah's Place
You'll always be a piece of mine, a piece of mine
We drove that road we know at least a million times
I'm so damn tired of seeing that empty drive
Out at Sarah's Place
Don't come back lover, I'm proud you're under the skyline
We always knew you were the better half of our good times
Those backyard lights don't shine as bright without your face
Out at Sarah's Place
Hey
Plane tickets have gotten awfully expensive

But I got mine for the price of a Gibson This last line is important as it references the line earlier where he said he had to sell his old guitar. He sold his guitar in an attempt to go home and feel like he did when he was younger.

div.head: Zach Bryan - Burn Burn Burn from a single that he released The song “Burn Burn Burn” by Zach Bryan has a theme of desire and acceptance. In the song, Zach discusses the desire he has for an authentic life without dealing with things that do not matter. He discusses his need to take time to focus on what is truly important to him and not what other people determine is important. The second theme of acceptance comes when he discusses that he wants a genuine life, he knows that there will be struggles and hardships and he is willing to accept that in order to have a life that he feels is an authentic life.

lg.l: Well, everyone seems a damn genius lately
TikTok talkin', late-night TV
There's still so much I have yet to know
Get dressed up just to go downtown
In some ego-filled late-night crowd
Seems to be where I feel most alone
I'd like to get lost on some old back road
And find a shade tree and a honey hole

And talk to my grandpa again From the beginning of the song up to this point, Zach is emphasizing the point that the "normal exciting life" is not for him and he wants a simple and peaceful life. One where he is able to sit and talk to his grandpa.
I'll see God in everything
Trees and pain and nights in the spring This line importantly includes the word "pain" acknowledging that he sees God, or the good, in everything, even the stereotypically bad.
So why do I still long for a home?
I'd like to lay in a field on a cozy blanket
And feel the fear of never wakin'
To know the true warmth of the sun
Like to love my lady long and hard
And lay down lines of laymen guitar
And never leave her lovin' arms again The previous four lines address feelings he wants to have. These are simple feelings that often get overlooked in life.
My exes hate me and my friends all miss me
I wanna drown in Rotgut whiskey
Leave this small town for a while
I wanna be a child climbin' trees somewhere
Breathin' in the fresh outside air
Before I knew this life was unkind The previous five lines express that he is aware of the negative in the world, and he is reminiscing about when he was younger and unaware of all this.
I want a well-trained dog on a couple of acres
A kind, kind lady and a place to take her
Few good friends I can count on one of my hands
I know I'm bound to die one day
So when I reach those golden gates

I pray to say I did the best I can These couple previous lines talk about the simple things that he wants in life that he feels would make him the most happy. He ends by saying that when he dies he hopes he is happy.
Sit with my mother and the dearly departed
Send a prayer down to the broken-hearted
Let 'em know it all turns out just fine These three lines talk about how he wants to tell people that no matter what it is ok and things will work out.
To know me is to love me and to hate me is to wrong me
I prefer my nights so lonely
Love blues guitar, muscle cars, and gin
'Cause I'm a simple man, I don't need much
Just my simple songs and some human touch
Tired now, so I'm bringin' my ass home
So let me go down the line
I wanna feel it all, joy, pain, and sky
So let me go down the line
'Cause we all burn, burn, burn and die
So let me go down the line
I wanna feel it all, joy, pain, and sky
So let me go down the line
We all burn, burn, burn and die
So let me go down the line
I wanna feel it all, joy, pain, and sky
Let me go down the line
We all burn, burn, burn and die
I got one more chorus for you guys if you wanna be in it
To the heavens, huh?
So let me go down the line
I wanna feel it all, joy, pain, and sky (let's go)
So let me go down the line
'Cause we all burn (burn, burn and die)

div.head: Zach Bryan - Open the Gate from the album American Heartbreak The song Open the Gate by Zach Bryan has a theme of legacy. It discusses the ideas of proving yourself and living up to expectations that the ones before you have set. The song sets the idea that there are risks that have to be taken to prove your worth. The song states that there is a “foolish pride” that comes along with trying to prove your worth, meaning you are willing to do whatever it takes to succeed. The song ends by ultimately saying that you will create your own legacy and eventually your own child will be tasked with living up to the legacy that you have left behind.

lg.l: ​​I heard you died out in Cheyenne
With my mother's ring on your hand
A note in your pocket said I love you till I die
I can hear the bulls are coming to claim what they've been huntin' These opening lines talk about the way narrators father had died.
The son of a cowboy can't claim his daddy's right
And my baby, she's been cryin' at the thought of me dyin'
She knows there's no stopping a man and his foolish pride
So, open the gates, I'm here to prove
I'm better than my father was
And where he came from, too This is the first time we get the idea of legacy. He is talking about taking on the feat that his father took on and proving his worth.
Open the gates, I'm here to ride To-hell-I-go, with daddy by my side
And I ain't never feared nothing that was four legged and buckin'
Throw me on a hurricane and I'll ride it to the coast
You'll never know that your son came to do what you should've done This line talks about that since his father died, there is no way for the father to know that the child is living up to the legacy.
On a summer day a long time ago, top a bull named To-hell-I-go
So, open the gates, I'm here to prove
I'm better than my father was
And where he came from, too
Open the gates, I'm here to ride To-hell-I-go, with daddy by my side
Will I die out in Cheyenne with my baby there cryin'?
In a belly that's been growin' by the day
And I know that my son will do what his father should've done
A long, long time ago on a bull named To-hell-I-go The last four lines talk about the never ending cycle of legacy chasing that will come from a child trying to achieve the goals set by the father.
So, open the gates, he's here to prove
He's better than his father was
And where he came from too
Open the gates he's here to ride To-hell-I-go's calf
The daddy by his side The last chorus was slightly changed to emphasize the passing on of the burden of the legacy to the son.
